00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.800
So I went as a musical
theater major, man.

00:42:48.800 --> 00:42:50.640
And it was going to Howard.

00:42:50.640 --> 00:42:53.790
And it was one of the best
decisions ever in my life.

00:42:53.790 --> 00:42:56.340
RYAN VUKELICH: Can you talk
about Howard and the role of

00:42:56.340 --> 00:42:59.810
historically black colleges and
universities and also of

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:01.170
Black History Month?

00:43:01.170 --> 00:43:01.810
ERIC ROBERSON: Indeed.

00:43:01.810 --> 00:43:05.320
You're walking down hallways
that Donny

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:08.430
Hathaway hummed down.

00:43:08.430 --> 00:43:10.370
You're going into practice
rooms that Roberta

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:11.800
Flack played in.

00:43:11.800 --> 00:43:15.360
You're standing on a stage
reading a monologue that

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:18.080
Phylicia Rashad read
a monologue on.

00:43:18.080 --> 00:43:19.990
Just a history of it.

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:24.270
And I learned very early
on to be very prepared.

00:43:24.270 --> 00:43:29.300
Because at any second, Q-Tip
from a Tribe Called Quest or

00:43:29.300 --> 00:43:32.960
Bill Cosby or Muhammad Ali will
walk down the hallway or

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:35.530
across the yard.

00:43:35.530 --> 00:43:39.580
But at the same time, my friends
were getting signed.

00:43:39.580 --> 00:43:42.060
If anybody remembers-- (SINGS)
and if I ever--

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:44.580
the group Shai, "Fall
in Love" song.

00:43:44.580 --> 00:43:45.550
We were friends.

00:43:45.550 --> 00:43:47.080
They were our buddies
at Howard.

00:43:47.080 --> 00:43:51.410
And they handed their
record to a DJ.

00:43:51.410 --> 00:43:55.950
And two weeks later, they're
on "Arsenio Hall." And five

00:43:55.950 --> 00:43:59.780
weeks later, they had finished
the album in a week, handed in

00:43:59.780 --> 00:44:01.210
the album, sold three
million copies.

00:44:01.210 --> 00:44:03.500
And I handed them my demo
and said just hand it

00:44:03.500 --> 00:44:04.310
to somebody in LA.

00:44:04.310 --> 00:44:05.680
Before I knew it, I
was flying there.

00:44:05.680 --> 00:44:08.160
And in my sophomore year,
I got a record deal.

00:44:08.160 --> 00:44:12.190
And so it was just a very
working environment.

00:44:12.190 --> 00:44:16.470
One of my professors, the late,
great amazing Al Freeman

00:44:16.470 --> 00:44:19.200
who played Elijah Muhammad in
the "Malcolm X" movie was one

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:20.530
of my teachers.

00:44:20.530 --> 00:44:23.210
And he shot it while teaching.

00:44:23.210 --> 00:44:27.440
So I'm like, I'm going to LA
next week to try to meet with

00:44:27.440 --> 00:44:28.290
Warner Brothers for
a record deal.

00:44:28.290 --> 00:44:30.830
Like how can he be like no,
stay here and work on your

00:44:30.830 --> 00:44:35.020
studies when he's like, I'm
going to meet with Spike.

00:44:35.020 --> 00:44:36.790
It was just a working
environment.

00:44:36.790 --> 00:44:38.420
Marlon Wayans was a good
friend of mine.

00:44:38.420 --> 00:44:41.010
He was doing movies and going
to class at the same time.

00:44:41.010 --> 00:44:43.220
So I think I needed
to see that.

00:44:43.220 --> 00:44:46.680
It was the first lesson of
learning how to balance

00:44:46.680 --> 00:44:47.350
everything.

00:44:47.350 --> 00:44:49.360
RYAN VUKELICH: Yeah.

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:50.900
That's a lot going on at once.

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:52.880
And I think inspiring to see.

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:53.100
ERIC ROBERSON: Very much.

