00:47:33.770 --> 00:47:35.460
ERIC ROBERSON: Yeah, there
was a whole album called

00:47:35.460 --> 00:47:39.950
"Esoteric." And it's crazy,
because it was a healing

00:47:39.950 --> 00:47:40.760
record for me.

00:47:40.760 --> 00:47:46.000
So when the album came out and
there were songs like--

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.540
what is some of the song titles?
"A Newborn Child,"

00:47:48.540 --> 00:47:51.020
which is saying I'll cry like
a newborn child, which I was

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:52.960
doing at the time.

00:47:52.960 --> 00:47:56.850
When the album came out and I
would meet women that were

00:47:56.850 --> 00:47:58.580
like, this record
is so beautiful.

00:47:58.580 --> 00:48:00.412
I'm like, what do you mean?

00:48:00.412 --> 00:48:04.280
It was about pain, you
horrible person.

00:48:04.280 --> 00:48:05.990
Like, don't ever listen
to my record.

00:48:05.990 --> 00:48:07.620
You don't understand.

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:10.300
But I had to realize that people
could relate to what I

00:48:10.300 --> 00:48:11.680
was going through,
and it helped.

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:15.360
It helped me heal, would
help them heal.

00:48:15.360 --> 00:48:18.740
There was a song called
"Miles Away" on it

00:48:18.740 --> 00:48:22.170
that was really important.

00:48:22.170 --> 00:48:24.890
And really, the record--

00:48:24.890 --> 00:48:28.490
esoteric means only meant to be
understood by chosen few.

00:48:28.490 --> 00:48:31.990
And that, to me,
was my career.

00:48:31.990 --> 00:48:33.280
I wasn't trying to
change the world.

00:48:33.280 --> 00:48:35.010
I wasn't trying to win
everybody over.

00:48:35.010 --> 00:48:36.910
I was trying to just do
music for someone

00:48:36.910 --> 00:48:38.550
who would feel this.

00:48:38.550 --> 00:48:42.530
Because I always felt like my
music career and my love life

00:48:42.530 --> 00:48:43.640
were parallel.

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:45.906
They always have been.

00:48:45.906 --> 00:48:47.910
And as a song writer,
I was doing great.

00:48:47.910 --> 00:48:49.150
I had songs for everybody
and their mother.

00:48:49.150 --> 00:48:50.090
I was writing all these songs.

00:48:50.090 --> 00:48:51.210
I was doing very, very well.

00:48:51.210 --> 00:48:54.550
But was I fulfilled with
what I was doing?

00:48:54.550 --> 00:48:57.440
I felt like I was a solo artist
writing, a lot of

00:48:57.440 --> 00:49:02.130
times, compromising or
as a fan, missing

00:49:02.130 --> 00:49:03.370
what was on the radio.

00:49:03.370 --> 00:49:07.570
So I said, all right, let me
start doing what I feel like

00:49:07.570 --> 00:49:08.530
I'm missing.

00:49:08.530 --> 00:49:10.170
And I think that's what I'm
still doing to this day.

00:49:10.170 --> 00:49:12.700
RYAN VUKELICH: That's great.

00:49:12.700 --> 00:49:14.322
I mean, I'll be real with you.

00:49:14.322 --> 00:49:15.650
I've healed from your music.

00:49:15.650 --> 00:49:17.750
And that's how I first
got into you.

00:49:17.750 --> 00:49:20.970
"Past Paradise," "Find a Way,"
those are songs that when you

00:49:20.970 --> 00:49:22.917
listen to, you're like, man,
he's been through it.

00:49:22.917 --> 00:49:23.095
Thanks.

00:49:23.095 --> 00:49:24.480
ERIC ROBERSON: Yeah, yeah.

00:49:24.480 --> 00:49:27.050
Make checks payable
to Eric Roberson.

00:49:27.050 --> 00:49:28.900
Whoever, you can just
fill it out.

00:49:28.900 --> 00:49:29.740
My father's back there.

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:30.990
He'll just accept the
checks and payments.

00:49:34.360 --> 00:49:39.070
I'll tell you, I say
this respectfully.

00:49:39.070 --> 00:49:41.285
I got a text earlier, and I
could show you for whoever

00:49:41.285 --> 00:49:44.206
doesn't believe me.

00:49:44.206 --> 00:49:47.060
The guy who I was talking to
who's in the industry, and

00:49:47.060 --> 00:49:49.220
he's struggling in
his travels.

00:49:49.220 --> 00:49:51.230
And he says, man, you
write great songs

00:49:51.230 --> 00:49:52.710
about passing up vaginas.

00:49:52.710 --> 00:49:56.470
And I was like, what a great
horrible compliment.

00:49:56.470 --> 00:49:58.020
That was like amazingly
horrible.

00:49:58.020 --> 00:49:59.290
Incredible at the same time.

00:49:59.290 --> 00:50:04.170
But for me, I realized a long
time ago-- what I will tell

00:50:04.170 --> 00:50:07.380
you is that the lyrics
come, and I can't

00:50:07.380 --> 00:50:08.730
take credit for them.

00:50:08.730 --> 00:50:11.440
They come, and then I learn
what they mean.

00:50:11.440 --> 00:50:13.710
And then I try to be good
enough to follow them.

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:14.700
You know what I mean?

00:50:14.700 --> 00:50:16.150
And that's been my
whole career.

00:50:16.150 --> 00:50:18.290
So it's like I'll a write a song
and go, wow, this sounds

00:50:18.290 --> 00:50:19.470
pretty good.

00:50:19.470 --> 00:50:23.480
And then the lyrics
are stable.

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:28.400
And then I learn what that
song meant for me.

00:50:28.400 --> 00:50:32.320
"Find a Way" was important
because it was--

00:50:32.320 --> 00:50:34.230
if anyone listens to "Find a
Way," it's a song of mine.

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:37.840
And it's like I sing it
two parts, one high

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:38.690
note and one low note.

00:50:38.690 --> 00:50:40.400
And I pan the high one all
the way to the right.

00:50:40.400 --> 00:50:42.090
And I pan the low one all
the way to the left.

00:50:42.090 --> 00:50:44.380
And the high one meant
to be emotion.

00:50:44.380 --> 00:50:46.600
And the low note meant
to be reality.

00:50:46.600 --> 00:50:48.420
And as a man, I was
battling that.

00:50:48.420 --> 00:50:51.660
Like sometimes we meet a young
lady and we're so used to our

00:50:51.660 --> 00:50:55.120
routine, she could be the soul
mate, but I got that game.

00:50:55.120 --> 00:50:56.690
I got to put that game on her.

00:50:56.690 --> 00:50:58.200
That I'm just ruining.

00:50:58.200 --> 00:51:00.480
Like, can I stop the game
for two seconds just

00:51:00.480 --> 00:51:01.980
to see who she is?

00:51:01.980 --> 00:51:07.450
And I've been lucky enough to
write about it or my breakups.

00:51:07.450 --> 00:51:09.770
I made a decision a long time
ago, when I went back to

00:51:09.770 --> 00:51:14.020
Howard, that every subject
that came to mind or

00:51:14.020 --> 00:51:14.540
everything.

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:16.760
I went through, I'll
put to music.

00:51:16.760 --> 00:51:20.960
So every argument, every great
day, every whatever, would be

00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:21.640
put to music.

00:51:21.640 --> 00:51:23.190
And I lost a lot of girlfriends
that way.

00:51:23.190 --> 00:51:27.060
It came with the good or bad.

00:51:27.060 --> 00:51:28.790
(SWEETLY) You wrote that
for me? (ANGRILY) You

00:51:28.790 --> 00:51:29.870
wrote that about me?

00:51:29.870 --> 00:51:35.660
It was the same thing, literally
24 hours apart.

00:51:35.660 --> 00:51:38.240
But it's something I
decided to do, man.

00:51:38.240 --> 00:51:41.140
And if God to allowed me to
have certain thoughts and

00:51:41.140 --> 00:51:44.530
lyrics and melodies, how
dare I not use them.

00:51:44.530 --> 00:51:45.490
RYAN VUKELICH: That's
incredible.

00:51:45.490 --> 00:51:46.550
So what's your process?

00:51:46.550 --> 00:51:49.070
Do you just wake up with
something in your

00:51:49.070 --> 00:51:50.150
head or does it vary?

00:51:50.150 --> 00:51:52.580
Because I know sometimes people
would say, oh, I woke

00:51:52.580 --> 00:51:53.620
up in the middle of the night.

00:51:53.620 --> 00:51:55.120
Sometimes I actually sat down.

00:51:55.120 --> 00:51:55.830
Does it change?

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:57.190
ERIC ROBERSON: It changes.

00:51:57.190 --> 00:51:58.860
I'm a fisherman of creativity.

00:51:58.860 --> 00:52:04.790
So I'm under the belief that
the idea already exists.

00:52:04.790 --> 00:52:07.300
I just have to find it
and make it tangible.

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:12.230
So a lot of my records are
written in the bathroom.

00:52:12.230 --> 00:52:15.310
I'll leave up to you to think
what's happening in the

00:52:15.310 --> 00:52:18.750
bathroom when I'm
writing them.

00:52:18.750 --> 00:52:22.160
But every aspect from shaving
to showering to

00:52:22.160 --> 00:52:23.510
other S words that--

00:52:23.510 --> 00:52:27.755
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:27.755 --> 00:52:28.400
ERIC ROBERSON: Soaping up.

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:28.730
RYAN VUKELICH: Situating.

00:52:28.730 --> 00:52:29.520
ERIC ROBERSON: Situating.

00:52:29.520 --> 00:52:30.770
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:52:33.890 --> 00:52:38.840
But it's funny, because before,
I was very much a

00:52:38.840 --> 00:52:40.040
slave to creativity.

00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:42.730
I was very much like if an idea
came and I was at the

00:52:42.730 --> 00:52:44.860
Thanksgiving table with my
family I haven't seen all

00:52:44.860 --> 00:52:46.970
week, I would get up right then
and go into the studio.

00:52:46.970 --> 00:52:49.919
I was very much like, I have
an idea, and everyone must

00:52:49.919 --> 00:52:51.130
respect the idea.

00:52:51.130 --> 00:52:53.420
Now, I believe that it's
going to come back now.

00:52:53.420 --> 00:52:58.830
So now having kids and having a
wife, I realize that that's

00:52:58.830 --> 00:53:01.920
a great idea, but I'm pushing
on the swing, and he's too

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:03.540
young to be left here.

00:53:03.540 --> 00:53:05.810
I mean, it'll come back.

00:53:05.810 --> 00:53:06.600
And it comes back.

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:08.140
It comes back.

00:53:08.140 --> 00:53:09.090
But I'm always writing.

00:53:09.090 --> 00:53:09.740
Always.

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:11.290
My phone is full of lyrics.

00:53:11.290 --> 00:53:13.310
And I'm always writing
letters.

00:53:13.310 --> 00:53:17.355
And I feel like you should just
write in general to stay

00:53:17.355 --> 00:53:18.870
in shape for when
the idea comes.

00:53:18.870 --> 00:53:20.030
RYAN VUKELICH: Definitely.

00:53:20.030 --> 00:53:20.900
You mentioned your kids.

00:53:20.900 --> 00:53:21.980
Just two more questions.

00:53:21.980 --> 00:53:24.430
One is what's one thing you
learned about yourself since

00:53:24.430 --> 00:53:27.160
you've become a father, which
was two years ago ish?

00:53:27.160 --> 00:53:27.880
ERIC ROBERSON: Yeah.

00:53:27.880 --> 00:53:30.030
I have a two-year-old and a
seven-month-old, and I'm not

00:53:30.030 --> 00:53:34.600
going to cry in front
of all these people.

00:53:34.600 --> 00:53:36.720
The thing I learned
about myself.

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:44.070
Man, I don't know.

00:53:44.070 --> 00:53:45.270
I learn about my kids.

00:53:45.270 --> 00:53:48.780
But I learned that I can
be a morning person.

00:53:48.780 --> 00:53:52.400
Because probably for the last 20
years, I've averaged waking

00:53:52.400 --> 00:53:55.300
up at 12:00 to 1:00
in the afternoon.

00:53:55.300 --> 00:54:03.010
And now my sons get up 7:30,
6:00 whatever in the morning.

00:54:03.010 --> 00:54:05.690
But I learned it's another
level of love, man.

00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:11.170
But it's tough, because I have
great parents who I knew the

00:54:11.170 --> 00:54:12.423
example of incredible love.

00:54:12.423 --> 00:54:14.480
I have amazing nephews
and nieces.

00:54:14.480 --> 00:54:16.970
And I was crazy over them.

00:54:16.970 --> 00:54:20.800
So I knew that it could exist
where it wasn't just more of

00:54:20.800 --> 00:54:23.520
an a-ha moment.

00:54:23.520 --> 00:54:28.106
But if anything, I learned that
you can balance it all.

00:54:28.106 --> 00:54:30.080
I will tell everybody out
there, there was a guy

00:54:30.080 --> 00:54:31.960
recently who I was just working

00:54:31.960 --> 00:54:34.110
with who was a cameraman.

00:54:34.110 --> 00:54:35.440
And he travels a lot.

00:54:35.440 --> 00:54:36.370
He just got married.

00:54:36.370 --> 00:54:38.320
He's like, my wife wants to have
a kid, but, man, I just

00:54:38.320 --> 00:54:39.280
travel too much, man.

00:54:39.280 --> 00:54:41.250
And I'm like, it's
going to fit.

00:54:41.250 --> 00:54:42.720
It's going to make
its way, man.

00:54:42.720 --> 00:54:46.120
Don't hold off for that.

00:54:46.120 --> 00:54:47.600
I don't think we
really waited.

00:54:47.600 --> 00:54:48.510
I didn't push it away.

00:54:48.510 --> 00:54:53.280
But now, my last two records I
recorded, a lot of time, my

00:54:53.280 --> 00:54:54.630
son was on my lap.

00:54:54.630 --> 00:54:55.590
Either one of them.

00:54:55.590 --> 00:54:55.910
You know what I mean?

00:54:55.910 --> 00:54:57.600
Because I got to get
this idea done.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:54:58.740
I want to spend time with him.

00:54:58.740 --> 00:55:00.750
And he wants to spend
time with me.

00:55:00.750 --> 00:55:01.690
Let's go in the studio.

00:55:01.690 --> 00:55:02.320
You know what I mean?

00:55:02.320 --> 00:55:03.270
And it just works.

00:55:03.270 --> 00:55:03.810
It just works.

00:55:03.810 --> 00:55:09.980
And I look forward to having
them one tour with me and the

00:55:09.980 --> 00:55:12.500
first time they actually write
a song or something like.

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:13.740
I look forward to all that.

00:55:13.740 --> 00:55:17.310
So I feel what I may learn is
just that my dreams are coming

00:55:17.310 --> 00:55:18.490
true, more and more.

00:55:18.490 --> 00:55:19.296
RYAN VUKELICH: Excellent.

00:55:19.296 --> 00:55:19.700
That's wonderful.

00:55:19.700 --> 00:55:22.450
So speaking of the studio,
last question.

00:55:22.450 --> 00:55:24.070
What's coming up next for you?

00:55:24.070 --> 00:55:27.060
I've heard United Tenor
is in the mix.

00:55:27.060 --> 00:55:27.800
ERIC ROBERSON: And I'm
not going to cry

00:55:27.800 --> 00:55:28.600
about this one either.

00:55:28.600 --> 00:55:30.270
I have to say that first,
because if I don't

00:55:30.270 --> 00:55:31.900
say it, I will cry.

00:55:31.900 --> 00:55:35.750
I started doing music because
of three influences.

00:55:35.750 --> 00:55:38.630
And one was A Tribe
Called Quest.

00:55:38.630 --> 00:55:40.280
Number two was Stevie Wonder.

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:42.565
And another was a group
called Commission.

00:55:42.565 --> 00:55:44.695
It was a gospel group from
Detroit called Commission.

00:55:44.695 --> 00:55:45.130
[CLAPPING]

00:55:45.130 --> 00:55:46.210
ERIC ROBERSON: Thank you.

00:55:46.210 --> 00:55:48.920
And one of the founders of that
group was a guy named

00:55:48.920 --> 00:55:52.510
Fred Hammond, an amazing
vocalist, amazing writer.

00:55:52.510 --> 00:55:56.810
And not only just musically,
but I remember as a kid

00:55:56.810 --> 00:55:59.320
hearing their music and going,
whatever that is,

00:55:59.320 --> 00:56:00.850
I want to do that.

00:56:00.850 --> 00:56:06.960
And I've had chances of meeting
Fred Hammond for many

00:56:06.960 --> 00:56:09.240
years, and I passed
up every time.

00:56:09.240 --> 00:56:15.680
And my staff and some friends
surprised me with a meeting.

00:56:15.680 --> 00:56:17.380
I'm in a restaurant thinking
I'm about be interviewed by

00:56:17.380 --> 00:56:18.680
Tom Joyner.

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:20.500
And in walks Fred Hammond.

00:56:20.500 --> 00:56:21.410
I tried to run away.

00:56:21.410 --> 00:56:22.720
And I was like, oh,
you got me.

00:56:22.720 --> 00:56:25.840
You got me, man.

00:56:25.840 --> 00:56:27.875
And just because I wanted to be
able to tell the man, like,

00:56:27.875 --> 00:56:30.250
yo, my career means so much--

00:56:30.250 --> 00:56:31.330
I'm not going to cry.

00:56:31.330 --> 00:56:31.790
Here we go.

00:56:31.790 --> 00:56:32.090
Ah, toughen up.

00:56:32.090 --> 00:56:33.650
Toughen up.

00:56:33.650 --> 00:56:34.390
Because of you.

00:56:34.390 --> 00:56:34.940
You know what I'm saying?

00:56:34.940 --> 00:56:37.040
I have this career, and I didn't
know if I was where I

00:56:37.040 --> 00:56:39.030
needed to be at yet to
really understand.

00:56:39.030 --> 00:56:40.380
I didn't want to just hear,
oh, that's cool, man.

00:56:40.380 --> 00:56:40.840
Thanks a lot.

00:56:40.840 --> 00:56:42.220
When are we going to eat?

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:44.775
I didn't want that
to be blown over.

00:56:44.775 --> 00:56:46.030
So we kept in touch.

00:56:46.030 --> 00:56:49.280
And then a couple of months ago,
he said, I got an idea.

00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:51.080
I want to form a new group.

00:56:51.080 --> 00:56:54.060
And I would love for you to
be a member of the group.

00:56:54.060 --> 00:56:55.610
And I was like, OK.

00:56:55.610 --> 00:56:57.885
I mean, I'll play the piccolo
on an album for Fred.

00:56:57.885 --> 00:56:59.020
I'll pay to do it.

00:56:59.020 --> 00:57:01.480
And it's not just me and him.

00:57:01.480 --> 00:57:03.430
It's Dave Hollister from
the group Blackstreet.

00:57:03.430 --> 00:57:05.260
An amazing solo artist.

00:57:05.260 --> 00:57:06.800
I'm a huge fan of Dave.

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:09.330
And another amazing artist named
Brian Courtney Wilson

00:57:09.330 --> 00:57:10.840
who I'm friends with already.

00:57:10.840 --> 00:57:13.300
I met him years ago, and
we kept in touch.

00:57:13.300 --> 00:57:14.780
And we all went to Dallas.

00:57:14.780 --> 00:57:18.180
And over the last month or so,
we travelled back and forth,

00:57:18.180 --> 00:57:20.040
and we recorded an
incredible album.

00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:24.660
And so the group's called
United Tenors or UT.

00:57:24.660 --> 00:57:26.230
The album comes out
March 26th.

00:57:26.230 --> 00:57:29.030
We had our first concert
last Saturday.

00:57:29.030 --> 00:57:30.690
We shot a music video
and live performance

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:33.290
for a crowd in Dallas.

00:57:33.290 --> 00:57:36.820
And we cried through
the whole show.

00:57:36.820 --> 00:57:40.940
All four are just literally--

00:57:40.940 --> 00:57:43.800
it's a dream come true, really,
in every aspect.

00:57:46.896 --> 00:57:50.240
We performed four songs and we
played the rest of the record.

00:57:50.240 --> 00:57:51.670
So while we're singing,
we're crying.

00:57:51.670 --> 00:57:52.690
While we're playing
the records for

00:57:52.690 --> 00:57:53.670
people, we're crying.

00:57:53.670 --> 00:57:57.480
Someone said something amazing
on stage, so literally, when

00:57:57.480 --> 00:57:59.675
you see the video, we're all
like this with just towels on

00:57:59.675 --> 00:58:01.810
our face through the
whole performance.

00:58:01.810 --> 00:58:05.220
But it's tears of joy.

00:58:05.220 --> 00:58:08.250
And we're probably not going to
stop crying anytime soon.

00:58:08.250 --> 00:58:12.380
In all honesty, 10, 20 shows
we're still going to be just

00:58:12.380 --> 00:58:16.400
like, (FAKE SOBBING) I just so
appreciate this opportunity.

00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:19.096
And it's a gospel album, man.

00:58:19.096 --> 00:58:20.140
I pride myself on it.

